post_text: Congratulations to Monte del Sol students Shayla Anthony, Nefi Guevara Perez, Max Montoya, and Hebert Soto, for their research, presentation, and computer model "Examining the Effects on Wildfire Spread" at the 30th annual New Mexico Supercomputing Challenge. The team won the Environmental Modeling Award from Los Alamos National Lab. Nefi and Max also received scholarships to New Mexico Tech. Congratulations team!

Please remain in communication with us and reach out to advisors, administration, counselors, etc., so we can assist in the ways we are able.

Thank you.

post_text: Congratulations to Monte del Sol teacher, Rhonda Crespo, who recently earned her National Board Certification in Biology. She joins more than 125,000 teachers nationwide who have achieved this honor. In order to become a Board-certified teacher, teachers complete a performance-based, peer-reviewed process, demonstrating their proven impact on student learning and achievement. Great job, Rhonda; we are proud of you!

post_text: Anne Frank: A History for Today Exhibit: Monte del Sol Charter School is one of four Santa Fe high schools to host the internationally acclaimed Anne Frank: A History for Today exhibit. Organized in Santa Fe by Anne Frank House and The Consulate General of the Netherlands, the exhibit has been shown in more than forty countries. The exhibit shows photographs of Anne Frank‚Äôs childhood in Frankfurt and in Amsterdam and portrays the rise of the Nazis, the persecution of the Jews and, very importantly, the way the people responded against the background of the Holocaust and WWII. Eight students from Monte del Sol have been trained to learn how to be tour guides and will explain the content to their fellow students and learn to challenge them to reflect on the historical events and to make relevant connections with is- sues in contemporary society. The exhibit will be at Monte del Sol, from April 4-8, 2019.

post_text:
ACTION NEEDED!!!!
There is a really important bill in discussion right now that could impact Monte del Sol dramatically. Monte del Sol has a diverse population that is 16% English Language Learners, 23% Special Education students, and 68% economically disadvantaged. 70% of our student population are minorities. SB1 would severely inhibit Monte del Sol‚Äôs ability to function. Monte del Sol receives a budget adjustment due to its smaller size, but SB1 would take that away and reduce our budget by at least $350,000. With the sorts of constraints on Monte del Sol‚Äôs annual budget it would be very difficult to operate Monte del Sol and keep our doors open. Yazzie v. State of New Mexico ruling is meant to help disadvantaged populations in New Mexico, passing this bill would hurt that exact population at Monte del Sol, which is a vast majority of our kiddos. Please PLEASE consider writing to the Governor in regards to this bill. Encourage her to separate the small schools funding from teacher raises! Thank you for your help and support for our school!
